&lt;/ref&gt; Projections consistently showed increase in annual world emissions of [[Kyoto Protocol|"Kyoto"]] gases,&lt;ref&gt;carbon dioxide, methane, nitrous oxide, sulfur hexafluoride&lt;/ref&gt; measured in [[carbon dioxide equivalent|{{CO2}}-equivalent]]) of 25–90% by 2030, compared to 2000.&lt;ref name="rogner summary of emission trends"/&gt;

===Clean Power Plan===
{{main|Clean Power Plan}}
The Clean Power Plan was an Obama administration policy aimed at combating global warming that was first proposed in 2014. The plan's goal was to move away from coal and instead use renewable energy or gas to generate electricity, which would reduce particulate matter in the environment. 
On March 1, 2017 [[Murray Energy|Murray Energy Corporation]] sent a letter to the Trump administration wherein they submitted an Action Plan [https://assets.documentcloud.org/documents/4345546/Murray-Energy-s-Action-Plan-for-the-Trump.pdf] "which will help getting America's coal miners back to work."  They listed their suggestions in the order of priority, with doing away with Obama's Clean Power Plan at the top of the list.  Second is doing away with the "endangerment finding" in the Clean Air Act. 
[https://www.nrdc.org/sites/default/files/epa-endangerment-finding-fs.pdf] The endangerment finding is the legal and scientific foundation for climate action.  Third is the elimination of tax credits for solar panels and windmills.  Fourth is to withdraw from the Paris Climate Accord.  Other suggestions include cutting back of EPA staffing to at least half.&lt;ref name="documentcloud.org"/&gt;  On March 28, 2017, Trump signed an executive order to officially withdraw and rewrite Obama's Clean Power Plan in what he believes will revive the coal mining industry and remove what he considers to be a needless burden on the U.S. automotive industry.&lt;ref name=":7"&gt;{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/28/climate/trump-executive-order-climate-change.html|title=Trump Signs Executive Order Unwinding Obama Climate Policies|last=Davenport|first=Coral|date=March 28, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 30, 2017|last2=Rubin|first2=Alissa J.|issn=0362-4331}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/03/28/climate/trumps-executive-order-pushes-the-us-climate-pledge-further-out-of-reach.html|title=Trump's Executive Order Pushes the U.S. Climate Pledge Further Out of Reach|last=Popovich|first=Nadja|date=March 28, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=March 30, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}&lt;/ref&gt; EPA staff emails obtained through a [[Freedom of Information Act]] request submitted by the [[Environmental Defense Fund]] in 2018 show that within days of Trump's announcement EPA director Scott Pruitt directed EPA staff to remove much of the climate change information from the agency's website and "[modify] search results for 'Clean Power Plan' to feature a page touting Trump's executive order featuring a photo of the president posing with smiling coal miners, Pruitt and other members of his cabinet."
&lt;ref name="auto12"/&gt;

The [[effects of global warming]] include [[rising sea levels]], regional changes in precipitation, more frequent [[extreme weather]] events such as [[heat wave]]s, and [[Desertification|expansion of deserts]].&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|IPCC AR5 WG2 Technical Summary|2014|pp=44–46}}; {{harvnb|D'Odorico|Bhattachan|Davis|Ravi|2013}}.&lt;/ref&gt; [[Ocean acidification]] is also caused by greenhouse gas emissions and is commonly grouped with these effects even though it is [[Effects of global warming on oceans|not driven by temperature]]. Surface temperature increases are [[polar amplification|greatest in the Arctic]], which has contributed to the [[retreat of glaciers since 1850|retreat of glaciers]], [[permafrost]], and [[sea ice]]. Overall, higher temperatures bring more rain and snowfall, but for some regions [[drought]]s and [[wildfire]]s increase instead.&lt;ref&gt;{{harvnb|National Geographic|2019}}; {{harvnb|NPR|2010}}.&lt;/ref&gt; Climate change threatens to diminish [[crop yields]], [[climate change and agriculture|harming food security]], and rising sea levels may flood coastal infrastructure and force the [[Environmental migrant|abandonment]] of many coastal cities.&lt;ref&gt;
{{Harvnb|Campbella|Vermeulen|Aggarwa|Corner-Dolloff|2016|p=}}; {{Harvnb|National Research Council|2012|pp=26–27}}.&lt;/ref&gt; Environmental impacts include the [[Extinction risk from global warming|extinction]] or relocation of many species as their [[Climate change and ecosystems|ecosystems]] change, most immediately the environments of [[Environmental issues with coral reefs|coral reefs]],&lt;ref&gt;
{{Harvnb|Knowlton|2001|p=}}.&lt;/ref&gt; [[Montane ecosystems|mountains]], and the [[Climate change in the Arctic|Arctic]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |ref=harv |url=https://19january2017snapshot.epa.gov/climate-impacts/climate-impacts-ecosystems_.html#Extinction |title=Climate Impacts on Ecosystems |author=EPA |date=19 January 2017 |access-date=5 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180127185656/https://19january2017snapshot.epa.gov/climate-impacts/climate-impacts-ecosystems_.html#Extinction |archive-date=27 January 2018 |url-status=live}}&lt;/ref&gt;

