'''Pine Island Glacier''' (PIG) is a large [[ice stream]], and the fastest melting glacier in Antarctica, responsible for about 25% of Antarctica's ice loss.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.livescience.com/43540-pine-island-glacier-past-thinning.html|title=History Repeating Itself at Antarctica's Fastest-Melting Glacier|year=2014|magazine=LiveScience}}&lt;/ref&gt; The glacier ice streams flow west-northwest along the south side of the [[Hudson Mountains]] into [[Amundsen Sea#Pine Island Bay|Pine Island Bay]], [[Amundsen Sea]], [[Antarctica]]. It was mapped by the [[United States Geological Survey]] (USGS) from surveys and [[United States Navy]] (USN) air photos, 1960–66, and named by the [[Advisory Committee on Antarctic Names]] (US-ACAN) in association with Pine Island Bay.&lt;ref name="gnisPineIslandGlacier" /&gt;&lt;ref name="PayneVieli2004" /&gt;

===Canada===
{{See also|Ward Hunt Island}}
[[File:Bylot Islandedit.png|thumb|280px|Bylot Ice Cap on Bylot Island, one of the [[Canadian Arctic islands]], August 14, 1975 (USGS)]]
The [[Canadian Arctic islands]] contain the largest area and volume of land ice on Earth outside of the Greenland and Antarctic Ice Sheets&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal | last1 = Radić | first1 = V. | last2 = Hock | first2 = R. | year = 2010 | title = Regional and global volumes of glaciers derived from statistical upscaling ofglacier inventory data | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/2c7639daf102f50ca62f76021e3b399a630856e5| journal = J. Geophys. Res. | volume = 115 | issue = F1| page = F01010 | doi=10.1029/2009jf001373 | bibcode=2010JGRF..115.1010R}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal | last1 = Sharp | first1 = M. | last2 = Burgess | first2 = D. O. | last3 = Cogley | first3 = J. G. | last4 = Ecclestone | first4 = M. | last5 = Labine | first5 = C. | last6 = Wolken | first6 = G. J. | year = 2011 | title = Extreme melt onCanada's Arctic ice caps in the 21st century | url = https://semanticscholar.org/paper/09019a5b355aaf9b50f403df00c9912e2aa2237d| journal = Geophys. Res. Lett. | volume = 38 | issue = 11| page = L11501 | doi=10.1029/2011gl047381 | bibcode=2011GeoRL..3811501S}}&lt;/ref&gt; and is home to a number of substantial ice caps, including [[Penny Ice Cap|Penny]] and [[Barnes Ice Cap|Barnes]] ice caps on [[Baffin Island]], Bylot Ice Cap on [[Bylot Island]], and [[Devon Ice Cap]] on [[Devon Island]]. Glaciers in the Canadian Arctic were near equilibrium between 1960 and 2000, losing 23 Gt of ice per year between 1995 and 2000.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal | author=W. Abdalatiia| title=Elevation changes of ice caps in the Canadian Arctic Archipelago | journal=Journal of Geophysical Research| date=2004| volume=109 | issue=F4 | pages=F04007| doi=10.1029/2003JF000045| url=https://www.nasa.gov/pdf/121645main_2003JF000045-1_pub_1.pdf| displayauthors=etal | hdl=2060/20040171503 | bibcode=2004JGRF..109.4007A }}&lt;/ref&gt; Since this time, Canadian Arctic glaciers have experienced a sharp increase in mass loss in response to warmer summer temperature, losing 92 Gt per year between 2007 and 2009 .&lt;ref&gt;{{cite journal | last1 = Gardner | first1 = A. S. | last2 = Moholdt | first2 = G. | last3 = Wouters | first3 = B. | last4 = Wolken | first4 = G. J. | last5 = Burgess | first5 = D. O. | last6 = Sharp | first6 = M. J. | last7 = Cogley | first7 = J. G. | last8 = Braun | first8 = C. | year = 2011 | title = Sharply increased mass loss from glaciers and ice caps in theCanadian Arctic Archipelago | url = https://zenodo.org/record/3425640| journal = Nature | volume = 473 | issue = 7347| pages = 357–360 | doi=10.1038/nature10089|bibcode = 2011Natur.473..357G | pmid=21508960}}&lt;/ref&gt;

The [[IPCC Third Assessment Report|third assessment report (TAR)]] prominently featured&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
| title=Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis
| authorlink=IPCC
| url=http://www.grida.no/climate/ipcc_tar/wg1/pdf/WG1_TAR-FRONT.pdf
}}&lt;/ref&gt; a graph labeled "Millennial Northern Hemisphere temperature reconstruction" based on a 1999 paper by [[Michael E. Mann]], [[Raymond S. Bradley]] and Malcolm K. Hughes (MBH99), which has been referred to as the "[[hockey stick graph]]". This graph extended the similar graph in [[:File:IPCC 1996 SAR Figure 3.20.png|Figure 3.20]] from the [[IPCC Second Assessment Report]] of 1995, and differed from a schematic in the [[MWP and LIA in IPCC reports|first assessment report]] that lacked temperature units, but appeared to depict larger global temperature variations over the past 1000 years, and higher temperatures during the [[Medieval Warm Period]] than the mid 20th century. The schematic was not an actual plot of data, and was based on a diagram of temperatures in central England, with temperatures increased on the basis of documentary evidence of Medieval [[Wine from the United Kingdom|vineyards in England]]. Even with this increase, the maximum it showed for the Medieval Warm Period did not reach temperatures recorded in central England in 2007.&lt;ref name="Jones 09"&gt;{{Cite journal| last1 = Jones | first1 = P. D.| last2 = Briffa | first2 = K. R.| last3 = Osborn | first3 = T. J.| last4 = Lough | first4 = J. M.| last5 = Van Ommen | first5 = T. D.| last6 = Vinther | first6 = B. M.| last7 = Luterbacher | first7 = J.| last8 = Wahl | first8 = E. R.| last9 = Zwiers | first9 = F. W.| last10 = Mann | first10 = M. E.| last11 = Schmidt | first11 = G. A.| last12 = Ammann | first12 = C. M.| last13 = Buckley | first13 = B. M.| last14 = Cobb | first14 = K. M.| last15 = Esper | first15 = J.| last16 = Goosse | first16 = H.| last17 = Graham | first17 = N.| last18 = Jansen | first18 = E.| last19 = Kiefer | first19 = T.| last20 = Kull | first20 = C.| last21 = Kuttel | first21 = M.| last22 = Mosley-Thompson | first22 = E.| last23 = Overpeck | first23 = J. T.| last24 = Riedwyl | first24 = N.| last25 = Schulz | first25 = M.| last26 = Tudhope | first26 = A. W.| last27 = Villalba | first27 = R.| last28 = Wanner | first28 = H.| last29 = Wolff | first29 = E.| last30 = Xoplaki | first30 = E.| title = High-resolution palaeoclimatology of the last millennium: a review of current status and future prospects| journal = The Holocene| volume = 19| issue = 1| pages = 3–49| year = 2009| url = http://shadow.eas.gatech.edu/~kcobb/jones09.pdf| doi = 10.1177/0959683608098952| bibcode = 2009Holoc..19....3J}} p. 36&lt;/ref&gt; The MBH99 finding was supported by cited reconstructions by {{harvnb|Jones|Briffa|Barnett|Tett|1998}}, {{harvnb|Pollack|Huang|Shen|1998}}, {{harvnb|Crowley|Lowery|2000}} and {{harvnb|Briffa|2000}}, using differing data and methods. The Jones et al. and Briffa reconstructions were overlaid with the MBH99 reconstruction in Figure 2.21 of the IPCC report.&lt;ref name="TAR 2.3.2.2"&gt;{{Harvnb|Folland et al.|2001}}, [http://www.grida.no/publications/other/ipcc_tar/?src=/climate/ipcc_tar/wg1/069.htm#fig220 2.3.2.2 Multi-proxy synthesis of recent temperature change] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110604072514/http://www.grida.no/publications/other/ipcc_tar/?src=%2Fclimate%2Fipcc_tar%2Fwg1%2F069.htm |date=4 June 2011 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

